            <article class="lg:col-span-7 prose prose-lg prose-slate max-w-none">
                <p class="lead text-xl text-slate-600 mb-8">Residential design has undergone a radical transformation over the past few decades. What once relied on drafting tables, T-squares, and graphite has evolved into a highly sophisticated digital ecosystem powered by Computer-Aided Design (CAD) and Building Information Modeling (BIM).</p>
                
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-4">The Era of Ink and Vellum</h2>
                <p>Before the late 20th century, every residential blueprint was meticulously hand-drawn. Architects spent hundreds of hours translating concepts onto vellum paper. Any major revision required starting entirely from scratch, making the design process slow, rigid, and prone to human error.</p>

                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-4">The CAD Revolution</h2>
                <p>The introduction of AutoCAD in the 1980s fundamentally shifted the paradigm. CAD allowed architects to create precise vector-based drawings on a computer screen. Revisions could be made instantly, layers could be toggled on and off for plumbing or electrical overlays, and drawings could be replicated infinitely without degradation in quality.</p>

                <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-brand-blue bg-slate-50 p-6 my-8 italic text-slate-700 rounded-r-lg">
                    "CAD did not just digitize the drawing process; it changed the very speed at which architectural thought could be visually expressed."
                </blockquote>

                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-4">The Rise of 3D and BIM</h2>
                <p>Today, 2D CAD is giving way to 3D BIM (Building Information Modeling). Tools like Revit allow designers to build a virtual, data-rich model of a home before a single brick is laid. This shift means clients can walk through their homes in virtual reality, and structural engineers can automatically detect clashes between HVAC systems and support beams.</p>
                
                <p>The evolution from manual blueprints to digital CAD, and now to intelligent BIM models, represents more than technological advancement—it represents a leap in creative freedom, safety, and efficiency in residential design.</p>
            </article>

